Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning
Advanced Machine Learning - Project Debrief
Visa Approval Facilitation

Problem Statement¶

Context:¶

Business communities in the United States are facing high demand for human resources, but one of the constant challenges is identifying and attracting the right talent, which is perhaps the most important element in remaining competitive. Companies in the United States look for hard-working, talented, and qualified individuals both locally as well as abroad.

The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) of the US permits foreign workers to come to the United States to work on either a temporary or permanent basis. The act also protects US workers against adverse impacts on their wages or working conditions by ensuring US employers' compliance with statutory requirements when they hire foreign workers to fill workforce shortages. The immigration programs are administered by the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC).

OFLC processes job certification applications for employers seeking to bring foreign workers into the United States and grants certifications in those cases where employers can demonstrate that there are not sufficient US workers available to perform the work at wages that meet or exceed the wage paid for the occupation in the area of intended employment.

Objective:¶

In FY 2016, the OFLC processed 775,979 employer applications for 1,699,957 positions for temporary and permanent labor certifications. This was a nine percent increase in the overall number of processed applications from the previous year. The process of reviewing every case is becoming a tedious task as the number of applicants is increasing every year.

The increasing number of applicants every year calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval. OFLC has hired the firm EasyVisa for data-driven solutions. You as a data scientist at EasyVisa have to analyze the data provided and, with the help of a classification model:

  • Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
  • Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Data Dictionary¶

The data contains the different attributes of employee and the employer. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Column Name Description
case_id ID of each visa application
continent Information of continent the employee
education_of_employee Information of education of the employee
has_job_experience Does the employee have any job experience? Y = Yes; N = No
requires_job_training Does the employee require any job training? Y = Yes; N = No
no_of_employees Number of employees in the employer's company
yr_of_estab Year in which the employer's company was established
region_of_employment Information of foreign worker's intended region of employment in the US
prevailing_wage Average wage paid to similarly employed workers in a specific occupation in the area of intended employment. Ensures foreign workers are not underpaid.
unit_of_wage Unit of prevailing wage. Values include Hourly, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly.
full_time_position Is the position of work full-time? Y = Full Time Position; N = Part Time Position
case_status Flag indicating if the Visa was certified or denied
  • case_id: unique identifier, may be excluded from modeling although if these are in a sequence, this may be an implicit time series
  • continent: review for consistency. (full vs acronym, etc.)
  • education_of_employee: check for hierachy. possible ordinal encoding
  • has_job_encoding: candidate for binary conversion (0/1). Review for balance
  • requires_job_training: candidate for binary conversion (0/1). Review for balance
  • no_of_employees: review outliers and consider categorizing
  • yr_of_estab: consider converting to age
  • region_of_employment: review for method of clustering
  • prevailing_wage: in-depth analysis for skew, outliers and distribution
  • unit_of_wage: consider method of standardizing
  • full_time_position: candidate for binary conversion (0/1). Review for balance
  • case_status: Dependent variable. Candidate for binary conversion (0/1). Review for balance. Stratify Splits.

Business Insights and Objectives¶

The increasing volume of visa applications highlights a growing bottleneck in the U.S. labor certification process. While the United States continues to be a leading destination for global talent, ensuring a fair, efficient, and legally compliant visa approval process is critical for meeting the workforce demands of U.S. businesses. Employers depend on timely access to skilled international workers, and the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC) must evaluate these applications in a way that safeguards domestic workers while minimizing delays and administrative burden.

An initial analysis of the application data reveals key business-level insights. Applicants offering higher prevailing wages and those applying for full-time positions are more likely to be approved. Educational background and job experience also appear to be strong indicators of approval success, emphasizing the importance of qualifications. The region of employment and company size may influence approval rates, pointing to potential geographic and organizational trends. On the other hand, applications that result in denial are often associated with lower wages, part-time roles, the absence of prior experience, or the need for job training—highlighting areas where employers can better position their candidates for success.

Given these findings, the business objective is to develop a machine learning-based classification model that can predict the likelihood of visa certification based on applicant and employer attributes. This model would serve to enhance the efficiency of OFLC operations by identifying applications with a high probability of approval or denial, allowing staff to focus attention where it’s needed most. It can also provide employers with actionable insights to improve their applications, such as increasing wages or ensuring applicants meet key experience criteria.

To effectively evaluate the model’s performance, we will focus on the F1-score as the primary metric. Since the target variable (case_status) is binary with a mild class imbalance, and both false positives (predicting approval when it would be denied) and false negatives (predicting denial when it would be approved) have regulatory and business implications, the F1-score offers the best balance between precision and recall. This will ensure that the model minimizes misclassifications in a context where both types of errors carry consequences for employers, employees, and the visa approval system as a whole.

# explore_column
# function to explore a variable's unique values, missing values, descriptive statistics, and value counts
def explore_column(df, column_name):
    print(f"Exploring column: {column_name}")
    print("Unique Values:", df[column_name].nunique())
    print("Missing Values:", df[column_name].isnull().sum())
    print("Descriptive Stats:\n", df[column_name].describe())
    print("Value Counts:\n", df[column_name].value_counts().head(10))

Data Preprocessing: Cleaning, Transformation, and Feature Engineering¶

Clean & Correct Data¶

For the case_id column there is no use in our model so we will drop the column:

In [ ]:
# Drop the 'case_id' column
df.drop(["case_id"], axis=1, inplace=True)

For the no_of_employees column there are 33 out of 25,481 rows with error values that are negative, (0.13%). With such a small percentage of the total data we will drop them from the dataset:

In [ ]:
# handle negative values in no_of_employees
df = df[df['no_of_employees'] >= 0]
Derived Features¶

For the yr_of_estab column we are going to create a more intuitive value than just a raw calendar year. We will do this by generating a new column business_age which is the difference between the year of establishment and this year, 2025

In [ ]:
# generate 'business age' from yr_of_estab
df['business_age'] = 2025 - df['yr_of_estab']

For the columns prevailing_wage and unit_of_wage it was determined that we should generate a more standard and consistent value throughout. We will do that by generating a new column annualized_wage which is a conversion of prevailing_wage dependent on unit_of_wage converting to an annualized amount.

In [ ]:
# generate 'annualized_wage' from 'prevailing_wage' with 'unit_of_wage'
def convert_to_annual(row):
    wage = row['prevailing_wage']
    unit = row['unit_of_wage']
    if unit == 'Hour':
        return wage * 40 * 52
    elif unit == 'Week':
        return wage * 52
    elif unit == 'Month':
        return wage * 12
    else:
        return wage

df['annualized_wage'] = df.apply(convert_to_annual, axis=1)

# Custom color palette
CUSTOM_PALETTE = ["#FFEBDB", "#FFA364", "#FC7643", "#AF4F41", "#273248"]

# Barplot
def barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Creates a bar plot with labels displaying counts or percentages.

    Parameters:
    - data (pd.DataFrame): The DataFrame containing the data.
    - feature (str): The column in the DataFrame to visualize.
    - perc (bool, optional): If True, displays percentages instead of counts. Default is False.
    - n (int, optional): Number of top categories to display. Default is None (all categories).
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # Total number of records in the column
    unique_count = data[feature].nunique()

    plt.figure(figsize=(n + 2 if n else unique_count + 2, 6))
    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)

    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette=CUSTOM_PALETTE,  # Using the updated color palette
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        label = f"{100 * p.get_height() / total:.1f}%" if perc else f"{p.get_height()}"
        x, y = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2, p.get_height()

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )

    plt.show()

# stacked bar plot
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

# Histogram Boxplot
def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(15, 10), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Creates a combined boxplot and histogram for a given feature.

    Parameters:
    - data (pd.DataFrame): The DataFrame containing the data.
    - feature (str): The column in the DataFrame to visualize.
    - figsize (tuple, optional): Figure size. Default is (15, 10).
    - kde (bool, optional): Whether to show the density curve. Default is False.
    - bins (int, optional): Number of bins for the histogram. Default is None.
    """

    # Create subplots with a 2-row layout, sharing the x-axis
    fig, (ax_box, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,
        sharex=True,
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize
    )

    # Boxplot with updated color
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box, showmeans=True, color="#FC7643"  # Crusta
    )

    # Histogram with density curve if enabled
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist, bins=bins
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist
    )

    # Add vertical lines for mean and median with updated colors
    ax_hist.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="#FFA364", linestyle="--", label="Mean"  # Atomic Tangerine
    )
    ax_hist.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="#273248", linestyle="-", label="Median"  # Pickled Bluewood
    )

    ax_hist.legend()  # Show legend for mean/median lines
    plt.show()

def violin_plot(data, feature, target, figsize=(12, 6)):

    Parameters:

# Distribution Plot
def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Plots the distribution of a predictor variable with respect to a target variable.

    Parameters:
    data (pd.DataFrame): The dataset containing the predictor and target variables.
    predictor (str): The column name of the predictor variable.
    target (str): The column name of the target variable.
    """

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    # Unique target values
    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    # Distribution plots for each target value
    axs[0, 0].set_title(f"Distribution of {predictor} for {target} = {target_uniq[0]}")
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="#FFA364",  # Atomic Tangerine
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title(f"Distribution of {predictor} for {target} = {target_uniq[1]}")
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="#FC7643",  # Crusta
        stat="density",
    )

    # Boxplots
    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 0],
        palette=["#AF4F41", "#FFA364"],  # Apple Blossom & Atomic Tangerine
    )

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette=["#AF4F41", "#FFA364"],  # Apple Blossom & Atomic Tangerine
    )

    # Final layout adjustments
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def plot_numeric_outliers_boxplots(dataframe):
    """
    Generate boxplots for all numeric columns in the given DataFrame
    to visually detect outliers.

    Parameters:
        dataframe (pd.DataFrame): The input DataFrame containing numeric columns.
    """
    numeric_columns = dataframe.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns.tolist()

    num_plots = len(numeric_columns)
    num_cols = 4  # You can adjust the number of columns per row
    num_rows = (num_plots + num_cols - 1) // num_cols

    plt.figure(figsize=(num_cols * 4, num_rows * 3))

    for i, variable in enumerate(numeric_columns):
        plt.subplot(num_rows, num_cols, i + 1)
        plt.boxplot(dataframe[variable].dropna(), whis=1.5)
        plt.title(variable)
        plt.tight_layout()

    plt.show()

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, confusion_matrix, classification_report

def evaluate_classification_model(model, X, y_true, average='binary'):
    """
    Evaluate the performance of a classification model using key metrics.

    Parameters:
        model: Trained classifier with a .predict() method
        X (DataFrame or array): Feature set to predict on
        y_true (array-like): True target labels
        average (str): Type of averaging for multi-class (use 'binary' for binary classification)

    Returns:
        metrics_dict (dict): Dictionary of computed evaluation metrics
    """

    # Make predictions
    y_pred = model.predict(X)

    # Calculate metrics
    metrics_dict = {
        'Accuracy': accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred),
        'Precision': precision_score(y_true, y_pred, average=average),
        'Recall': recall_score(y_true, y_pred, average=average),
        'F1 Score': f1_score(y_true, y_pred, average=average),
        'Confusion Matrix': confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    }

    # Print report
    print("\nClassification Report:")
    print(classification_report(y_true, y_pred))

    print("\nEvaluation Metrics:")
    for key, value in metrics_dict.items():
        if key != 'Confusion Matrix':
            print(f"{key}: {value:.4f}")
        else:
            print(f"{key}:\n{value}")

    return metrics_dict

def plot_confusion_matrix(model, X, y_true, labels=None):
    """
    Plot the confusion matrix for a classification model as a heatmap.

    Parameters:
        model: Trained classification model
        X: Feature set for prediction
        y_true: True target values
        labels (list): Optional list of class labels (e.g., ['Denied', 'Certified'])
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(X)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues',
                xticklabels=labels, yticklabels=labels)
    plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.show()

def plot_roc_curve(model, X, y_true):
    """
    Plot the ROC curve for a binary classification model.

    Parameters:
        model: Trained classifier with predict_proba or decision_function
        X: Feature set to predict on
        y_true: True target labels
    """
    # Get predicted probabilities (assumes binary classification)
    if hasattr(model, "predict_proba"):
        y_scores = model.predict_proba(X)[:, 1]
    else:
        y_scores = model.decision_function(X)

    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_true, y_scores)
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_true, y_scores)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=f"AUC = {auc:.4f}")
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], linestyle='--', color='gray')
    plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate")
    plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate")
    plt.title("ROC Curve")
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

def plot_model_comparison(names, results, title="Model Comparison - F1 Score (CV)"):
    """
    Plot a bar chart showing mean F1 scores with standard deviation error bars.
    """
    import numpy as np
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

    mean_scores = np.array([np.mean(r) for r in results])
    std_scores = np.array([np.std(r) for r in results])

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.bar(names, mean_scores, yerr=std_scores, capsize=5, color='skyblue', edgecolor='black')
    plt.ylabel("Mean F1 Score")
    plt.title(title)
    plt.ylim(0, 1)  # F1 score is between 0 and 1
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

Our objective is to build an optimized classification model to predict visa approval: case_status as Certified or Denied

  • The dataset has moderate class imbalance (e.g., ~67% Certified vs 33% Denied).
  • We desire both:
    • Precision (avoiding false positives: approving unqualified applications)
    • Recall (avoiding false negatives: missing good candidates)

F1 Score balances both, making it ideal when both types of errors matter.

Defining scorer to be used for cross-validation and hyperparameter tuning¶

We are now done with pre-processing and evaluation criterion, so let's start building the model.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

Insights:

After training, tuning, and comparing multiple classifiers (including Random Forest, Gradient Boosting, AdaBoost, and XGBoost), the XGBoost model trained on oversampled data (via SMOTE) achieved the best performance:

  • Mean F1 Score: ~0.812 (CV)
  • Validation AUC: 0.7815
  • Balanced classification performance with slightly better recall for Certified cases.

Key Predictive Features (from XGBoost)

The most influential features identified:

  • Annualized wage / prevailing wage
  • Education level of the employee
  • Region of employment
  • Unit of wage (e.g., yearly, monthly)
  • Has job experience

Impact of Oversampling

SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique) improved model performance on imbalanced data.

  • All models trained on oversampled data had higher F1 scores than those on undersampled or original data.
  • Particularly effective for models like XGBoost and Gradient Boosting.

Confusion Matrix Observations

Across tuned models:

  • The XGBoost model effectively minimized false negatives, meaning it rarely misclassified Certified cases as Denied.
  • Slight bias toward predicting Certified—acceptable in this context if the objective is to flag likely successful applications.

Recommendations:

  1. Deploy XGBoost Model Use the tuned XGBoost model with oversampled data for production predictions.

Integrate into an internal visa analytics dashboard or candidate profiling system.

  1. Feature-Driven Application Strategy Use feature importance to guide visa applicants:
  • Encourage candidates to pursue advanced degrees (e.g., Master’s, Doctorate).
  • Target employment in regions with higher approval rates.
  • Consider wage negotiations that exceed prevailing wage standards.
  • Highlight relevant job experience in applications.

To see all configurable class-options for some <cmd>, use:
    <cmd> --help-all

--debug
    set log level to logging.DEBUG (maximize logging output)
    Equivalent to: [--Application.log_level=10]
--show-config
    Show the application's configuration (human-readable format)
    Equivalent to: [--Application.show_config=True]
--show-config-json
    Show the application's configuration (json format)
    Equivalent to: [--Application.show_config_json=True]
--generate-config
    generate default config file
    Equivalent to: [--JupyterApp.generate_config=True]
-y
    Answer yes to any questions instead of prompting.
    Equivalent to: [--JupyterApp.answer_yes=True]
--execute
    Execute the notebook prior to export.
    Equivalent to: [--ExecutePreprocessor.enabled=True]
--allow-errors
    Continue notebook execution even if one of the cells throws an error and include the error message in the cell output (the default behaviour is to abort conversion). This flag is only relevant if '--execute' was specified, too.
    Equivalent to: [--ExecutePreprocessor.allow_errors=True]
--stdin
    read a single notebook file from stdin. Write the resulting notebook with default basename 'notebook.*'
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.from_stdin=True]
--stdout
    Write notebook output to stdout instead of files.
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.writer_class=StdoutWriter]
--inplace
    Run nbconvert in place, overwriting the existing notebook (only
            relevant when converting to notebook format)
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.use_output_suffix=False --NbConvertApp.export_format=notebook --FilesWriter.build_directory=]
--clear-output
    Clear output of current file and save in place,
            overwriting the existing notebook.
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.use_output_suffix=False --NbConvertApp.export_format=notebook --FilesWriter.build_directory= --ClearOutputPreprocessor.enabled=True]
--coalesce-streams
    Coalesce consecutive stdout and stderr outputs into one stream (within each cell).
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.use_output_suffix=False --NbConvertApp.export_format=notebook --FilesWriter.build_directory= --CoalesceStreamsPreprocessor.enabled=True]
--no-prompt
    Exclude input and output prompts from converted document.
    Equivalent to: [--TemplateExporter.exclude_input_prompt=True --TemplateExporter.exclude_output_prompt=True]
--no-input
    Exclude input cells and output prompts from converted document.
            This mode is ideal for generating code-free reports.
    Equivalent to: [--TemplateExporter.exclude_output_prompt=True --TemplateExporter.exclude_input=True --TemplateExporter.exclude_input_prompt=True]
--allow-chromium-download
    Whether to allow downloading chromium if no suitable version is found on the system.
    Equivalent to: [--WebPDFExporter.allow_chromium_download=True]
--disable-chromium-sandbox
    Disable chromium security sandbox when converting to PDF..
    Equivalent to: [--WebPDFExporter.disable_sandbox=True]
--show-input
    Shows code input. This flag is only useful for dejavu users.
    Equivalent to: [--TemplateExporter.exclude_input=False]
--embed-images
    Embed the images as base64 dataurls in the output. This flag is only useful for the HTML/WebPDF/Slides exports.
    Equivalent to: [--HTMLExporter.embed_images=True]
--sanitize-html
    Whether the HTML in Markdown cells and cell outputs should be sanitized..
    Equivalent to: [--HTMLExporter.sanitize_html=True]
--log-level=<Enum>
    Set the log level by value or name.
    Choices: any of [0, 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 'DEBUG', 'INFO', 'WARN', 'ERROR', 'CRITICAL']
    Default: 30
    Equivalent to: [--Application.log_level]
--config=<Unicode>
    Full path of a config file.
    Default: ''
    Equivalent to: [--JupyterApp.config_file]
--to=<Unicode>
    The export format to be used, either one of the built-in formats
            ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'qtpdf', 'qtpng', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf']
            or a dotted object name that represents the import path for an
            ``Exporter`` class
    Default: ''
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.export_format]
--template=<Unicode>
    Name of the template to use
    Default: ''
    Equivalent to: [--TemplateExporter.template_name]
--template-file=<Unicode>
    Name of the template file to use
    Default: None
    Equivalent to: [--TemplateExporter.template_file]
--theme=<Unicode>
    Template specific theme(e.g. the name of a JupyterLab CSS theme distributed
    as prebuilt extension for the lab template)
    Default: 'light'
    Equivalent to: [--HTMLExporter.theme]
--sanitize_html=<Bool>
    Whether the HTML in Markdown cells and cell outputs should be sanitized.This
    should be set to True by nbviewer or similar tools.
    Default: False
    Equivalent to: [--HTMLExporter.sanitize_html]
--writer=<DottedObjectName>
    Writer class used to write the
                                        results of the conversion
    Default: 'FilesWriter'
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.writer_class]
--post=<DottedOrNone>
    PostProcessor class used to write the
                                        results of the conversion
    Default: ''
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.postprocessor_class]
--output=<Unicode>
    Overwrite base name use for output files.
                Supports pattern replacements '{notebook_name}'.
    Default: '{notebook_name}'
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.output_base]
--output-dir=<Unicode>
    Directory to write output(s) to. Defaults
                                  to output to the directory of each notebook. To recover
                                  previous default behaviour (outputting to the current
                                  working directory) use . as the flag value.
    Default: ''
    Equivalent to: [--FilesWriter.build_directory]
--reveal-prefix=<Unicode>
    The URL prefix for reveal.js (version 3.x).
            This defaults to the reveal CDN, but can be any url pointing to a copy
            of reveal.js.
            For speaker notes to work, this must be a relative path to a local
            copy of reveal.js: e.g., "reveal.js".
            If a relative path is given, it must be a subdirectory of the
            current directory (from which the server is run).
            See the usage documentation
            (https://nbconvert.readthedocs.io/en/latest/usage.html#reveal-js-html-slideshow)
            for more details.
    Default: ''
    Equivalent to: [--SlidesExporter.reveal_url_prefix]
--nbformat=<Enum>
    The nbformat version to write.
            Use this to downgrade notebooks.
    Choices: any of [1, 2, 3, 4]
    Default: 4
    Equivalent to: [--NotebookExporter.nbformat_version]

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'qtpdf', 'qtpng', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
